('how-to-travel-with-dog-safely',
 'How to Travel with Your Dog Safely — Complete Road Trip Guide',
 'Planning a road trip with your dog? This complete guide covers car safety, packing essentials, rest stops, and emergency preparedness for US pet travel.',
 '<h2>Planning a Safe Road Trip with Your Dog</h2>
<p>Over 78 million dogs live in US households, and 56% of dog owners take their pets on road trips. But a fun adventure can turn dangerous without proper planning.</p>
<h2>Step 1: Secure Your Dog Properly</h2>
<p>An unrestrained 60-pound dog in a 35 mph crash generates <strong>2,700 pounds of force</strong>. Proper restraint protects your dog AND everyone else in the car.</p>
<h3>Best Restraint Options by Dog Size</h3>
<ul><li><strong>Small dogs (under 20 lbs)</strong>: Booster seat or crash-tested carrier</li><li><strong>Medium dogs (20-50 lbs)</strong>: Crash-tested harness attached to seatbelt</li><li><strong>Large dogs (50+ lbs)</strong>: Crash-tested harness only</li></ul>
<p>See our <a href="/best-dog-car-seat-safety">complete car seat safety guide</a> for top crash-tested options.</p>
<h2>Step 2: Pack a Dog Travel Kit</h2>
<h3>Must-Have Items</h3>
<ul><li>Collapsible water bowl + 1 gallon of water per day</li><li>Enough food for the trip + 2 extra days</li><li>Leash, collar with ID tags, and harness</li><li>Waste bags</li><li>Familiar blanket or toy from home</li><li>Recent photo of your dog on your phone</li></ul>
<h3>First Aid Kit</h3>
<ul><li>Gauze pads and medical tape</li><li>Hydrogen peroxide (for vet-guided use only)</li><li>Benadryl (1 mg per pound — confirm with vet)</li><li>Tweezers for tick removal</li><li>Your vet''s phone number + ASPCA Poison Control: (888) 426-4435</li></ul>
<h2>Step 3: Plan Your Rest Stops</h2>
<p>Dogs need breaks every 2-3 hours for potty, water, and 10-15 minutes of walking.</p>
<h2>Step 4: Never Leave Your Dog in a Parked Car</h2>
<p>On an 85°F day, a car interior reaches 104°F in 10 minutes and 119°F in 30 minutes — even with windows cracked.</p>
<h2>Step 5: Handle Dog Car Anxiety</h2>
<p>25% of dogs experience travel anxiety. Our detailed guide on <a href="/how-to-stop-dog-anxiety-in-car">how to stop dog car anxiety</a> covers the step-by-step desensitization protocol.</p>
<ul><li>Use an anxiety vest 15 minutes before departure</li><li>Play calming music</li><li>Provide a stuffed KONG for distraction</li><li>Keep the car cool (65-72°F)</li></ul>
<h2>Gear Up for Safe Adventures</h2>
<p>Find <a href="/best-dog-car-seat-safety">crash-tested dog car seats</a>, <a href="/best-dog-anxiety-solutions">calming products for anxious dogs</a>, and browse our <a href="/dog/dog-car-travel-safety">dog car travel safety hub</a>. Your next adventure awaits!</p>',
 'Dog Travel',
